descr.name: qHTS assay to test for compound auto fluorescence at 535 nm (green) in HepG2 cell free culture
description: National Center for Advancing Translational Sciences [NCATS]
National Institutes of Environmental Health Sciences [NIEHS]

Compound auto fluorescence often interferes with screening of the compound library against various biological targets and signaling pathways. Some of these compounds may have fluorophoric properties. Such properties may interfere with the assay outputs resulting in false positives and/or negatives. To decrease such complications and ensure the compound activities are relevant in terms of biological response, the Tox21 10K compound library was screened for auto fluorescence.

From the fluorophores used as reporter signals in our screening assays, the auto fluorescence equivalencies of compounds against three fluorophores have been evaluated: Triamterene, Fluorescein and Rose Bengal sodium for blue, green and red fluorescence, respectively. The fluorescence intensities were measured using Excitation/Emission wavelengths at 405/460nm, 485/535nm and 540/590nm for blue, green and red labels, respectively. This assay includes the green fluorescence data.
protocol: 5 uL of culture medium (MEM containing 10% FBS) per well was dispensed into black wall/clear bottom 1536-well plates using a Multidrop Combi Dispenser (ThermoFisher Scientific, Waltham, MA). After 23 nL compound or DMSO vehicle was transferred into assay plate by a pintool work station (Kalypsys, San Diego, CA), fluorescence intensities in the assay plates were measured by an Envision (PerkinElmer, Shelton, CT) plate reader using three labels for measuring blue, green and red fluorescence at excitations 460, 535 and 590nm respectively.
comment: 1. Compounds are first classified as having full titration curves, partial modulation, partial curve (weaker actives), single point activity (at highest concentration only), or inactive. See data field "Curve Description". For this assay, apparent activators are ranked higher than compounds that showed apparent inhibition.

2. For all inactive compounds, PUBCHEM_ACTIVITY_SCORE is 0. For all active compounds, a score range was given for each curve class type given above.  Active compounds have PUBCHEM_ACTIVITY_SCORE between 40 and 100.  Inconclusive compounds have PUBCHEM_ACTIVITY_SCORE between 1 and 39.  Fit_LogAC50 was used for determining relative score and was scaled to each curve class' score range.

Although all reasonable efforts have been made to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the data, caution should be exercised when interpreting the results as artifacts are possible from nonspecific effects such as assay signal interference. The curve fitting and activity calls presented here are based on the NCATS analysis methods. Alternative analysis methods and interpretations of the data are available at EPA (http://actor.epa.gov) and NTP (http://tools.niehs.nih.gov/cebs3/ui/).

description: Indicates type of activity observed: inhibitor, activator, fluorescent, cytotoxic, inactive, or inconclusive.

description: Concentration at which compound exhibits half-maximal efficacy, AC50. Extrapolated AC50s also include the highest efficacy observed and the concentration of compound at which it was observed.

results.name: Efficacy-Replicate_1
description: Maximal efficacy of compound, reported as a percentage of control. These values are estimated based on fits of the Hill equation to the dose-response curves.

description: Annotation/notes on a particular compound's data or its analysis.

results.name: Curve_Description-Replicate_1
description: A description of dose-response curve quality. A complete curve has two observed asymptotes; a partial curve may not have attained its second asymptote at the highest concentration tested. High efficacy curves exhibit efficacy greater than 80% of control. Partial efficacies are statistically significant, but below 80% of control.

description: R^2 fit value of the curve. Closer to 1.0 equates to better Hill equation fit.

results.name: Potency-Replicate_14
description: Concentration at which compound exhibits half-maximal efficacy, AC50. Extrapolated AC50s also include the highest efficacy observed and the concentration of compound at which it was observed.

results.name: Efficacy-Replicate_14
description: Maximal efficacy of compound, reported as a percentage of control. These values are estimated based on fits of the Hill equation to the dose-response curves.

results.name: Analysis Comment-Replicate_14
description: Annotation/notes on a particular compound's data or its analysis.

results.name: Curve_Description-Replicate_14
description: A description of dose-response curve quality. A complete curve has two observed asymptotes; a partial curve may not have attained its second asymptote at the highest concentration tested. High efficacy curves exhibit efficacy greater than 80% of control. Partial efficacies are statistically significant, but below 80% of control.

description: The asymptotic efficacy from a fit of the data to the Hill equation.
